Is there a black box in your car?
While American road designers are trying to find money to repair the crumbling highway system, many are beginning to see the solution in a small black box neatly attached to your car’s dashboard.
These devices, which track every mile traveled by a motorist and transmit this information to officials, are at the center of a controversial attempt to modernize America’s outdated highway financing system, undertaken by Washington and state planning authorities.
The usually boring motorway planning arena has suddenly spawned intense debate and colorful alliances.
Libertarians have joined environmental groups in lobbying to give the government the right to use small boxes to track the number of miles you drive, and even perhaps where you drive them, and then use that information when compiling tax bills.
The tea party is in shock.
The American Civil Liberties Union is also deeply concerned and raises a number of questions regarding privacy.
And although Congress cannot yet agree on whether to proceed or not, several states are not going to wait.
Over the next decade, they are pondering how to move to a system in which drivers pay for every mile of road they drive.
Thousands of motorists have already taken these black boxes for testing, some of which have a satellite tracking function.
This is really necessary for our country.
“It’s not a matter on which we may have a choice,” said Hassan Ihrata, executive director of the Southern California Government Association, which is preparing plans to begin tracking the state’s miles traveled by every California motorist by 2025.
There will be changes in how we pay those taxes.
The technology for that already exists.
The need for this is compounded by the lack of funds from the Government's Highway Construction Fund, funded by taxes Americans pay at gas stations.
Americans don’t buy as much gasoline as they used to.
Cars travel more miles per gallon.
The federal tax itself, 18.4 cents per gallon, hasn’t been raised in 20 years.
Politicians do not want to raise the tax even by one cent at high gasoline prices.
“A gasoline tax simply can’t be saved,” said Lee Mannich, a transportation policy expert at the University of Minnesota.
In his state, 500 tracking devices were recently installed on cars to test the system of erroneous payment.
“This will be the best alternative in the long run,” he said.
Boring people call this the wrong user fee.
Unsurprisingly, the idea attracts urban liberals, as taxes could change the nature of travel to reduce road congestion and greenhouse gas emissions, for example.
Planning authorities in California are eyeing the system as they develop strategies to meet targets set by that state’s ambitious global warming laws.
However, Rep. Bill Schuster (Republican, Pennsylvania), chairman of the House Transportation Committee, said he, too, sees the system as the most viable long-term alternative.
Free market advocates at the Reason Foundation are also thrilled to make drivers pay for every mile.
“It’s not just a tax that’s going to go into a black hole,” said Adrian Moore, vice president of political affairs at Reason.
People pay directly for what they get.
The move is also supported by two former U.S. transport ministers, who in 2011 called on Congress to move in the direction of mispayment.
The U.S. Senate approved a $90 million pilot project last year that would have involved about 10,000 vehicles.
House leaders, however, rejected the proposal because of concerns from rural legislators representing voters, who often have to travel miles to get to work or to the city in their daily lives.
Several states and cities, however, are following this path on their own.
The greatest enthusiasm is shown in Oregon, where 5,000 drivers are involved in the largest experiment in the country.
These drivers will soon be paying the state for miles of mileage instead of a gasoline tax.
In Nevada, the pilot project has already been completed.
It is under consideration in New York.
Illinois will trial it on a limited basis involving trucks.
And the I-95 coalition, which includes the transport departments of 17 states on the east coast (including Maryland, Pennsylvania, Virginia and Florida), is exploring how they can make these changes.
This concept has not been universally accepted.
In Nevada, where about 50 volunteer cars were recently fitted with these devices, drivers were concerned that the government could track their every move.
“Worrying about big brother and things like that is a big problem,” said Alauddin Khan, head of strategy and performance management at the Nevada Department of Transportation.
It wasn't what people wanted.
When the tests were in full swing, the Nevada branch of the American Civil Liberties Union warned on its website: “It will not be difficult to turn these devices into full-scale tracking devices.”
There is no need to create a huge, cumbersome technological infrastructure, which will inevitably expand to store records of the daily movements of individual citizens.
Nevada is one of several states that are struggling to find a low-cost technology that would allow state authorities to keep records of driving miles, but without information about the place and time.
If you can do that, Khan said, society will feel more at ease.
The search for this technology led some state agencies to a small young company in California called True Mileage.
Initially, this company did not assist in the collection of state taxes.
It sought to enter the emerging market of a type of auto insurance in which drivers pay on the basis of mileage.
But the devices it’s testing attract road designers because they don’t use GPS and provide a limited amount of information periodically downloaded using a modem.
“People will be more likely to do this if you don’t track their speed and track their location,” said Ryan Morrison, executive director of True Mileage.
There have been some big mistakes in some of these state pilot programs.
There are much less expensive and less intrusive ways to do this.
In Oregon, designers are experimenting with providing drivers with a variety of options.
They can choose a device with or without GPS.
Or they may abandon the device altogether, opting instead to pay a flat fee based on the average number of miles that all state residents drive.
Elsewhere, they hope to sell the idea to a wary public, forcing devices to do more, not less.
In New York City, transport officials are keen to develop a tax-deductible device that will also accept payment by parking meters, provide "pay as you drive" insurance, and collect a pool of real-time speed data from other drivers that motorists could use to avoid traffic jams.
“The motorists will be attracted to participate in the benefits that will be offered to them”, — stated in the document of urban design.
Some transport system designers, however, wonder if all the talk of mispayment is just a huge distraction.
Officials at the city’s San Francisco Bay Area Transportation Commission say Congress could very easily overcome the bankruptcy of the highway trust fund by raising gasoline taxes.
An additional one-time or annual tax could be levied on hybrid car drivers and others whose vehicles do not use a lot of gasoline to make them pay their fair share.
“There’s no need for radical surgery when all you have to do is take aspirin,” said Randy Rentschler, director of the Commission on Legislation and Public Relations.
If we do that, hundreds of millions of drivers will worry about their privacy and a host of other things.
The EU is preparing measures to support Ukraine in the event of economic pressure from Russia
The European Union has a contingency plan to provide Ukraine with gas, as well as to reach an agreement with the IMF on an emergency loan, if Russia takes any measures in response to the possible signing of an association agreement between the EU and Ukraine at the Vilnius summit.
Stand-by talks are under way with the IMF, and another EU official directly involved in the talks added that their goal is to conclude an agreement in the near future.
At the same time, in addition to a potential loan from the IMF, Ukraine can receive 610 million euros from the European Union itself.
Analysts interviewed by Reuters doubt that Ukraine and the IMF are able to overcome long-standing disagreements about the terms of financing.
Nor does the international rating agency S&P, which downgraded Ukraine’s sovereign rating on Friday to B- from B-, believe in the possibility of reforms needed to get help.
However, EU representatives say that the IMF can show flexibility in terms of lending, taking into account the circumstances of Ukraine.
In addition to the plan of financial support for the country, the EU has a backup option for providing Ukraine with gas, the vast majority of whose supplies are now coming from Russia.
Perhaps it will be gas from Nord Stream or reverse gas from Slovakia.
The latter, according to officials, is the most possible and acceptable way if Russia “isolates” Ukraine.
Analysts believe that this method of reverse deliveries to Ukraine can be used only for several weeks, and will likely lead to a decrease in supplies to other regions.
"Negotiations are underway between EU countries and Ukrainians on how to create favorable conditions so that Ukraine can import gas from other sources, not from Russia, or from the same source, but on other routes," the source added.
Russia out of the fight for pollution of cities by cars
Attempts to solve the transport problems of large cities have been observed in most megacities of the world since the second half of the twentieth century.
As a rule, it was either about their reconstruction and expansion of highways, or about attempts to reduce the demand for road travel, the number of cars and the time of their use.
The example of Singapore is widely known, where a strict quota of growth in the number of private cars is introduced, and the right to purchase them is bought at auctions.
Its price can be two to three times higher than the price of the car itself.
European cities, including London, have introduced a fee for entry into the city center.
In Germany, for example, in Hamburg and Stuttgart, the so-called green zones are introduced, which are allowed to enter only cars with a certain eco-class, using also high-quality fuel (including biofuels or electric cars).
Beijing’s Environmental Protection Agency, for example, approved a “five-year clean air plan” in 2012 with a total value of about 250 billion yuan (about $40 billion).
According to Li Kunsheng, Director of the Transport Pollution Control Department of the Beijing Municipal Environmental Protection Bureau, the main goal of the five-year plan is to reduce leading air pollutants by 20-35% by 2017, increase the number of private cars to no more than 6 million (now 5.2 million), as well as an increase of no more than 5% in fuel use per vehicle.
According to the agency, motor vehicles in Beijing are now responsible for 22.5% of total air pollution.
Among the main measures of the program is the restriction of the use of road transport, as well as the introduction of additional taxes for car owners.
Among other things, the city measures of the “green five-year plan” include an accelerated transition to European fuel standards compared to the rest of the country, the introduction of a local system of eco-standards and labeling of cars and fuel, restrictions on the entry of cars into the central part of the city, a ban on the use of outdated vehicles (in addition, the creation of incentive financial programs for replacing old cars with hybrid or electric vehicles), the development of electric transport (including public and official), the development of public high-speed transport.
Beijing's automotive innovations also include a ban on all private cars moving within the fifth transport ring (there are six of them in the capital of China) one day a week (the relevant information is contained in the license plate of the vehicle), as well as the issuance of registration plates for cars based on the lottery (for example, in 2011, the first year of the lottery, the total number of permits for registration of private cars in Beijing was only a third of the number of 2010).
According to the current state program "Environmental Protection for 2012-2020", the number of cities with high and very high air pollution should be reduced to 128 (in 2012 there were 138).
According to the Ministry of Natural Resources, in 2011, mobile sources accounted for 41% of all emissions of pollutants into the atmosphere of cities.
In Moscow, for example, emissions from cars are ten times higher than industrial, and in St. Petersburg - nine times.
In Russia, they are just beginning to think about the possibilities of restrictive regulation of cars on the streets of cities.
Mikhail Blinkin, Director of the HSE Institute of Transport Economics and Transport Policy, believes that administrative and fiscal measures aimed at suppressing the demand for road travel are obviously unpopular, they can be adopted by society only if they are completely universal.
In the case of Moscow, there is a unique problem associated with the structure of its fleet, where there are two clusters of weakly sensitive to any regulatory influences - official and personal cars, as well as cars of "privileged" users, the total number of which is at least 200 thousand (about 5% of the total number of Moscow fleet).
Recently, urbanists from the ECOM center in St. Petersburg prepared a study that analyzes the balance of urban areas between residential development, road surface area and the number of vehicles.
The main conclusions of the researchers: the city center is provided with roads twice less than required, and most motorists living in the center do not use cars every day, leaving them for a long time in parking lots or just on the streets.
As a result, it is proposed to build not parking, but car storage, not to expand, but to reduce the roadway (so that the streets become more pedestrian-friendly), as well as to limit the use and placement of personal transport within the boundaries of the territory of the historic center’s security zone (a total area of about 3,212 hectares covering a number of central areas of the city).
Fines for unauthorized street trade in Vologda will grow significantly
According to the city authorities, the increase in fines will help to restore order in Vologda and free the streets from spontaneous tents and trays.
Most street vendors don’t pay taxes, and the products they sell often don’t pass proper sanitary controls.
And this means that the health of moisture is at risk.
Thus, the lower limit of the fine for citizens for unauthorized trade from November will increase six times - from 500 rubles to 3000 rubles, the press service of the Vologda Administration.
Goldman Sachs warned about the risks to the Russian economy
Goldman Sachs warned about the growing risks to the main driver of fragile economic growth in Russia - consumption.
This is primarily a crisis of non-payments on unsecured consumer loans and massive cuts in workers.
Our main concern now is not that growth has slowed, but rather the pattern of that growth.
Recently, it is entirely due to consumption, which almost does not slow down,” said the chief economist of Goldman Sachs for Russia Clemens Grafe, presenting yesterday the quarterly report of the investment bank on the Russian economy.
Currently, nominal wage growth in Russia is about 10%.
With inflation of 6%, it will be able to provide future consumer demand at about the current level, Goldman Sachs expects.
But the profitability of Russian companies is falling, so, most likely, they will engage in optimization of personnel costs.
Today we see a significant increase in the share of wages in GDP: if wages grow by 10%, then GDP - only by 2%, - explained Mr. Grafe.
Companies are facing a decline in profitability.
If it does not grow, it can lead to layoffs and increased unemployment.
Russian business cannot not raise wages, comments Vladimir Pantyushin, chief economist for Russia and the CIS at Barclays Capital.
Unemployment near historical lows, competition for workers is high.
To lure employees away or keep the current ones, employers have to raise salaries.
Consumption in Russia is also supported by a very rapid growth in consumer lending.
According to Mr. Grafe, due to the extremely high rates on consumer loans, this type of lending does not have a multiplicative effect on the country's economy.
"We did not see any benefits for the economy from the growth of consumer lending, money does not diverge in the economy, but returns to the same banks in the form of interest payments," the economist said.
But the problem is different - Goldman Sachs expects an increase in overdue unsecured loans.
They are taken mainly by poor people who have nothing to provide.
Interest rates on such loans are high.
As a result, they are often not returned,” said Mr. Grafe.
Therefore, the second threat to the growth of the economy in Russia is a possible crisis of non-payments on unsecured loans.
Director of the HSE Banking Institute Vasily Solodkov is already seeing signs of a looming banking crisis.
Small credit institutions, without access to cheap resources, such as those of state-owned banks, were forced to attract funds from the population at high interest rates.
In response, the state-owned banks took the path of war and began to reduce credit rates, the economist continues.
Small credit institutions cannot issue loans at the same interest rate, otherwise they will have a negative interest margin.
If state-owned banks do not abandon dumping, Russia faces a full-fledged banking crisis, believes Vasily Solodkov.
Deprivation of the licenses of a number of banks in recent weeks, the economist considers a harbinger of a mass collapse.
"State banks themselves will not cope with this situation: the deposit insurance system was not originally designed for a systemic crisis," the head of the institute warns.
But the growth of consumption will slow down without a crisis of non-payments, the investment bank believes, due to the refusal to index the salaries of civil servants and the military, laid down in the current version of the draft budget.
Partially, the impact on consumption will be mitigated by the freezing of tariffs of natural monopolies (and, as a result, a decrease in inflation).
But only partially: if investment does not grow (and there are no prerequisites for this yet - see the certificate), consumption growth will still slow down, Goldman Sachs is sure.
Vladimir Pantyushin from Barclays Capital does not yet see the prerequisites for the implementation of pessimistic scenarios.
“The main risk is still the fall in the price of oil,” he says.
According to him, the Russian economy will begin to shrink at oil prices below $ 90 per barrel.
Goldman Sachs also noted that the Central Bank is not yet able to reduce interest rates in the economy.
There is a paradoxical picture: inflation has decreased, and banks have begun to raise rates.
This may mean that they did not believe the Central Bank, which announced the transition to inflation targeting,” said Clemens Grafe.
The interest rate policy of the Central Bank does not affect market rates, affects only interbank lending rates.
“For the Central Bank, this is the collapse of all hopes,” Clemens Grafe estimated.
Money received at auctions of the Central Bank, banks are used not to lend to the economy, but to manage their liquidity
As soon as the rate decreases, the exchange rate changes immediately, this means that the funds are trying to go to speculation against the ruble.
“Sooner or later, the Central Bank will understand that this strategy does not work,” said Mr. Grafe and recalled that the state plans to put the ruble into “free navigation” by the end of 2015.
But it will either have to do it sooner or raise the key rate of the Central Bank (5.5%), he said.
According to him, the ruble is now artificially inflated by 10%.
Ruble only one way - to weaken, - the expert concludes.
But if the Central Bank casts a shadow of doubt in the financiers that the liquidation of the currency corridor is not part of the policy to weaken the ruble, it can bring down the ruble much stronger.
