Snowden ready to ‘collaborate’ with Germany on U.S. intelligence
Edward Snowden, a U.S. intelligence whistleblower, said he was willing to travel to Berlin to testify to the German parliament if the U.S. National Security Agency and its director Keith Alexander could not answer questions about their activities.
German MP Hans-Christian Strebele met with Mr. Snowden in Russia on Thursday, where he has been granted asylum to discuss his testimony in Germany.
A letter from Mr Snowden, which the MP presented to the media in Berlin on Friday, said: “Although the result of my efforts has been clearly positive, my government continues to treat dissent as treason and seeks to criminalize political speech with criminal charges that do not provide any protection.”
But telling the truth is not a crime.
In the letter, Mr. Snowden said he believed that the support of the international community could persuade the U.S. government to drop criminal charges against him.
Charges filed by the U.S. Department of Justice include espionage and theft of state property.
Hans-Peter Friedrich, Germany’s interior minister, told Zeit Online: “If Mr. Snowden is willing to talk to German officials, we will find ways to make that possible.”
Relations between the U.S. and Germany have become tense after allegations that the NSA tapped Chancellor Angela Merkel’s phone.
Thomas Opperman, the MP who heads the parliamentary group overseeing the intelligence service, said that if there is an opportunity to listen to Mr. Snowden as a witness, “without endangering him or destroying relations with the United States completely,” it should be used.
Mr Stroebele, a member of parliament from Germany’s Green Party, posted his photo with Mr Snowden on Twitter.
During his visit to Russia, he was accompanied by two German journalists.
Mr Stroebele said that according to the lawyer of a former NSA contractor, Mr Snowden could not have returned to Russia if he had left.
Had Mr Snowden testified in Germany, he would have needed assurances that he would be there “safe,” the MP said.
Mr Snowden said in a letter that he faced a “tough and persistent” harassment campaign that forced him to leave his home.
However, he said he was encouraged by the world’s reaction to “his political remarks.”
Citizens around the world, as well as senior officials — including in the United States — have found exposing an unchecked system of pervasive surveillance beneficial to society.
The letter contains a proposal to cooperate with the German authorities “when the difficulties of this humanitarian situation are resolved.”
Frontier Airlines will charge for hand luggage
Frontier Airlines plans to charge passengers up to $100 for carrying hand luggage on board its flight.
Frontier Airlines plans to start charging up to $100 for carry-on luggage and $2 for coffee or soda, though their announcement on Wednesday said passengers would be able to keep the entire can.
The new hand luggage fee applies to bags in the upper luggage compartments, so small bags placed under the seat will remain free.
Frontier said it would charge $25 if the fee is paid in advance, and $100 if travelers only pay when they are at the boarding gate.
Frontier spokeswoman Kate O'Malley said the $100 fee should make passengers take care of the payment in advance.
“We don’t want to charge for that,” she said.
Airlines began charging for the first and second bags checked into their luggage in 2008.
Passengers trying to avoid these charges stuff as much as they can in hand luggage placed in the upper luggage compartments, which is why there is often not enough space in these compartments.
Fees are one way to get passengers to carry less on board.
O'Malley said this new collection isn't really about making money.
The fact is that the most loyal Frontier customers say that it is becoming increasingly difficult to find a place in the upper luggage compartments.
Passengers who buy tickets on the airline’s website will not have to pay.
This means that one passenger in the queue at the exit of the Frontier flight can get the opportunity to carry the bag for free, while the next passenger in the queue can pay $ 100 for the same bag.
O'Malley said the change to procedures on the website and at Frontier's check-in counters is designed to ensure passengers will be aware of the fee before they get to the boarding gate.
Frontier's new hand luggage charge won't start until summer, though the date has yet to be set.
Passengers often complain about baggage charges and other charges, but airlines love them.
They argue that baggage handling costs money, and passengers who need this service have to pay for it.
Many on Wall Street see the addition of baggage charges as a sign that airlines are charging enough money to cover the cost of air travel after years of losses.
However, most of them did not concern hand luggage fees.
Spirit Airlines Inc. introduced the first hand luggage charge three years ago, and another discounter, Allegiant Air, later followed suit.
The only other airline with such a fee is Hungarian Wizz Air, said airline consultant Jay Sorensen, who closely monitors the surcharges.
He estimated in a December 2011 report that a hand luggage fee earns Spirit $50 million a year.
Sorensen, a former Midwest Airlines executive, recently flew a Spirit flight and was wondering what he would find at the boarding gate when passengers faced an unusual Spirit hand luggage charge.
“The landing process was the smoothest I’ve seen in my career in airlines,” he said.
I was expecting to see a gnashing of teeth and a fight at the exit of the landing.
The plane was full, he said, “and the landing was quick.”
Frontier also follows Spirit for a $2 fee for coffee, tea, soda, or juice.
Frontier said passengers who receive soda or juice can keep the entire jar and that coffee will be provided free of charge.
It will continue to distribute water free of charge.
US Airways briefly tried to charge for drinks in 2008, but refused to do so seven months later, after passengers began to complain and no other major airline followed suit.
Frontier’s initiative to charge for hand luggage when passengers don’t buy tickets directly from the airline is its latest measure to attract customers to its website.
Airlines pay online ticket sellers like Orbitz between $10 and $25 for each ticket sold.
This gave all airlines an incentive to encourage passengers to buy tickets directly from them, rather than contacting an online travel agency.
However, Frontier has gone further in this area.
In September, she began giving half as many frequent flyer bonus miles to customers who bought tickets through an online travel agency.
On Wednesday, she cut the premium number of miles to 25 percent of the miles traveled.
So, a trip of 1000 miles with Frontier, purchased from an online travel agency, would allow you to get 250 miles.
In addition, passengers can choose a seat in advance only if they buy tickets directly on the Frontier website.
Frontier has a loyal customer base in her hometown of Denver, but its business is shrinking and becoming unprofitable.
Revenue fell 9 percent, and flight capacity declined nearly 13 percent in the first quarter, according to financial results released Wednesday by parent company Republic Airways Holdings Inc.
Republic is trying to fix Frontier's finances as part of the airline's sale.
NSA Blames ‘Internal Mistake’ Not Hackers for Shutting Down Website
The National Security Agency, shrouded in secrecy, said Friday night that the shutdown of their site for several hours caused a technical failure, not hackers, as claimed on the network.
"NSA.gov was unavailable for several hours tonight due to an internal error that occurred during the scheduled update," the intelligence agency said in an official email.
The problem will be solved tonight.
Claims that the outage was caused by a distributed denial-of-service attack [DDoS] are incorrect.
Earlier this evening, online server monitoring systems registered that the NSA site had not been operational for at least six hours, and the site is still unavailable to some users.
Earlier, an NSA official told ABC News that the agency’s internal secret network “wasn’t” hacked.
No classified information is at risk, the spokesman said.
At least one online group of hacker activists said it was responsible for disabling the NSA website with a DDoS attack.
DDoS attacks are designed to overwhelm the target site with traffic until the servers are overloaded and the site fails.
Hackers’ tactics are relatively simple, and the attacks are not designed to penetrate the target system’s internal network.
The previously top-secret NSA, once nicknamed “No Such Agency,” has been the focus of public attention and fierce criticism in recent months after a string of revelations about its extensive surveillance programs abroad and domestically — all in reaction to secret NSA files stolen from the agency and published by a disillusioned former NSA employee, Edward Snowden.
The growing controversy surrounding the agency has led to speculation that today’s incident was the result of targeted actions by hackers.
Bombardier's profit declines with falling deliveries and aircraft orders
Bombardier, a Canadian aircraft and train manufacturer, said on Thursday it had reduced net profit by 15 percent due to a decline in orders and deliveries in the third quarter and problems with contracts at its rail division.
Bombardier, based in Montreal, also did not release any data on flight tests of its newest aircraft CSeries and did not provide new information on whether ambitious plans will be fulfilled to put the aircraft into commercial operation by next September.
After the first flight of the prototype aircraft, which took place about a month and a half ago, it flew only three more times, which raises questions about whether the test stage is on schedule.
The results did not justify the forecasts and led to a drop in shares of more than 8 percent on the Toronto Stock Exchange.
Cameron Doerksen, an analyst at National Bank Financial, downgraded his valuation from “above the market average” to “average” on Thursday because of a belief that stock growth is limited in the coming quarter or two.
“While the decline in aircraft deliveries was generally predictable, we are certainly disappointed with the transport department’s profit margins,” Doerksen said in a stock market review.
We believe Bombardier will receive new orders for CSeries as the flight test program continues.
However, unless new orders are announced in the coming months, we expect the market to become more skeptical of the program.
Bombardier hopes that the CSeries family of aircraft will allow it to win a place in the lower price segment of the market, which is now dominated by Boeing and Airbus.
The first prototype of the aircraft was presented in March and first flew in September after several months of delay.
However, firm orders for CSeries are still not too much - 177, as potential buyers are waiting for the results of flight tests to check the company's claims about the fuel efficiency and potential economy of the new liner.
In total, there are 403 orders and agreements with 15 customers and operators.
Chief Executive Pierre Baudouin was confident that Bombardier would reach its target of 300 firm orders by the time the first aircraft was put into commercial operation.
On Thursday, executives also assured analysts and media outlets that the program was moving ahead as planned.
“The test model of the aircraft did not stay on the ground longer than expected,” Boduan said during a conference call, adding that ground tests and software updates were planned for the downtime of the aircraft.
All manufacturers plan tests differently.
We decided to conduct the first flight and take a break for updates, so we did.
This will be the case throughout the flight test program.
The second of the five test samples is due to fly in the coming weeks and everyone else will follow shortly, the company said.
Still, analysts are skeptical about the claim that the first customer will be able to start operating the CSeries aircraft 12 months after its first flight.
Bombardier said it is evaluating the commissioning date and will provide new information in the next few months.
"This slow pace of flight testing - though apparently consistent with Bombardier's internal schedule - reinforces our view that commissioning will be pushed back to the first quarter of 2015," Doerksen said.
In the third quarter ended September 30, Bombardier’s net income dropped to $147 million, or 8 cents per share, from $172 million, or 9 cents per share, last year.
Adjusted earnings per share remained the same - 9 cents.
Gross income declined slightly, from $4.2 billion to $4.1 billion.
Analysts had expected earnings of 10 cents per share and gross revenue of $4.56 billion, according to Thomson Reuters I/B/E/S.
The world’s fourth-largest aircraft manufacturer said it delivered 45 aircraft in the quarter, down from 57 the previous year.
The total number of orders fell from 83 to 26 aircraft.
The portfolio of orders of the aerospace department amounted to $32.9 billion as of September 30, unchanged from December 31.
“In the aerospace field, the results were in line with our goals, but the small number of incoming orders and general market conditions were an unpleasant factor,” Boduan said.
Gross aerospace revenue fell 13 percent to $2 billion.
Bombardier, the world’s largest train manufacturer, said gross revenue in the sector rose nearly 11 percent to $2.1 billion.
The portfolio of orders in the transport division amounted to $ 32.6 billion as of September 30, which is slightly higher than the figure of December 31.
The revenues of the transport unit were negatively affected by problems with the execution of several large contracts.
Management said that a new development plan will be presented in the fourth quarter.
Shares of Bombardier, which also announced that Google’s chief financial officer Patrick Pichett will join the board of directors, fell 8.5 percent to C$4.83 at auction in mid-Thursday.
Brazilian company Embraer SA, the world's third-largest commercial aircraft manufacturer and Bombardier's closest competitor, reported a 10 percent decline in quarterly revenue on Thursday.
Sony expects lower annual profit
Japanese electronics manufacturer Sony, ending the quarter with a net loss of 19.3 billion yen, or $197 million, reduced its forecast for profit for the current fiscal year.
Sony’s July-September 2013 results were more disappointing than expected, driven by a drop in demand for TVs, video cameras and personal computers manufactured by the Japanese corporation.
Sony’s TV business, which generated its first operating profit of 5.2 billion yen in three years in the second quarter, again fell to 9.3 billion yen in operating losses in the reporting period.
