The gene of speech was a stimulant for the formation of synapses
Scientists from Johns Hopkins University and Mount Sinai Medical School have discovered a protein that makes Foxp2’s speech gene function by stimulating the formation of new connections between neurons.
The study is published in Science, on the website of the journal you can read its brief content.
The Foxp2 gene is the first known gene whose function is directly related to speech.
It was possible to establish his role in 2001 thanks to the discovery of a family of several people who could not pronounce the words correctly and sometimes did not even understand each other.
Scientists have found that family members have been disrupted by the Foxp2 gene, but how it performs its function, it remained unknown.
In the new study, biologists have shown that at least part of its functions Foxp2 performs as a stimulator of the formation of new synapses in the brain area associated with the formation of speech.
He does this thanks to another gene, SRPX2.
The latter was discovered as a result of a search for factors that stimulate the formation of synapses.
SRPX2 turned out to be one of 10 similar genes found by the authors, while Foxp2 only affects its activity.
The fact that SRPX2 really affects vocalization, scientists have confirmed in an experiment on mice.
When the animals’ gene activity was artificially reduced, they screamed less when separated from their mother.
If the gene activity was restored, the frequency of sounds was also restored.
Previously, the mice also showed a connection to the vocalization of Foxp2 itself.
Animals injected with a human copy of the gene cried more actively and at a lower frequency than normal mice.
Until now, however, scientists don’t know whether Foxp2’s work and, accordingly, the SRPX2 it controls is related to purely “mechanical” properties of sound formation or finer processes.
Lawyer with cocaine addiction, who warned the leader of the criminal group about the police investigation, is imprisoned
42-year-old Basharat Ditta passed information to criminal authority Neil Scarborough
