He was sentenced to three years in prison by the Royal Liverpool Court.
A prestigious lawyer who told a drug lord about a major police investigation because he feared exposing his secret drug addiction was jailed for three years.
42-year-old Basharat Ditta gave criminal authority Neil Scarborough secret information about the investigation of his activities on drug trafficking after he was threatened because of his cocaine addiction.
The lawyer, nicknamed Bash and nicknamed a "cool lawyer" among criminals, was arrested at his home in 2011 after a police operation to spy on Scarborough, whom he had previously represented at a drug court.
Officers noticed the 32-year-old Scarborough leaving three bags of cocaine outside a lawyer's home in Blackburn, Lancashire, while he was at a lawyers' association dinner with colleagues.
The investigation revealed that Ditt “regularly used” a Class A drug, after tests showed traces of cocaine in his hair, on his wallet and on his credit cards.
For eight months from January to August 2011, he tried to illegally obtain information about the arrests of two people on behalf of Scarborough, as well as one of his accomplices.
All four suspects were under police surveillance at the time as part of an extensive investigation into the activities of a criminal organization selling heroin and cocaine in Lancashire, Cumbria, Merseyside, Berkshire and West Yorkshire.
They and 32 other people were later jailed after police seized heroin and cocaine worth 1.5 million euros in a series of raids, as well as more than 200,000 euros in cash.
Ditta, 42, passed on information to criminals out of fear that his cocaine addiction would be revealed.
Today, Ditt, who works for the law firm Forbes Solicitors, based in Blackburn, was covered with shame after pleading guilty to two counts of intentionally obstructing justice at the end of a three-week trial at Liverpool Crown Court.
He admitted to possession of cocaine at a previous trial.
The lawyer's exposure came after police investigating Scarborough found that he had spoken to Ditt on the phone regularly since February 2011.
Two detectives followed the suspect and found him walking up to Ditt's house in Blackburn and putting 60 percent pure black golf glove drugs under the lawyer's trash cans.
Soon after the transfer Scarborough repeatedly called with Ditt, who was at a dinner at the football stadium Ewood Park team "Blackburn Rovers".
The lawyer returned home for drugs; nine conversations took place between them.
The court learned that Ditt was “regularly using” cocaine after tests found traces of the Class A drug in his hair, wallet and on his credit cards.
Ditta was later arrested, but denied using cocaine, said he had spoken to the suspected dealer because he was his client, and insisted that their communication constituted an "advocacy secret".
During his detention, Ditt took his wallet and tried to take out several credit cards, but they were all confiscated, he also had a sample of hair taken.
When questioned by the police, he said that along with the workplace, he had a home office, and clients came to his house for legal affairs.
However, the court learned that after important arrests, he called the largest participants in drug trafficking, a number of which he previously represented in court to tell what detectives know about them.
In the indictment, Anne White said, “If anyone knows that you shouldn’t break the law, it’s a criminal defense attorney.”
Mr. Ditta is accused of abusing his position as a criminal lawyer because he has entered into too close a relationship with certain clients.
The contact we are talking about is not just a drug dealer, but a drug dealer supplying his own lawyer with drugs.
Some of his conversations will certainly prove to be legitimate, as he was their lawyer.
However, this has largely crossed the boundaries of the normal lawyer-client relationship.
He obstructed the police investigation as much as possible to allow these individuals to continue their criminal activities.
Mr. Ditta did not honor his profession, but disgraced it.
He got too close to certain clients, particularly Scarborough, and allowed his disinterest to be questioned.
Ditta pleaded not guilty and stated, "If I were a corrupt lawyer, which I am not, and I wanted to pass the information on to Mr Scarborough, I wouldn't have waited 15 hours, I would have done it immediately."
But after the hearing, Senior Officer Lee Halstead of Lancashire Police said, “Mr. Ditta went from a criminal lawyer to a criminal as soon as he started buying drugs from organized crime.”
His addiction to cocaine made him hopelessly compromised and vulnerable to the main targets of criminal gangs, who instructed him to obtain valuable information about police investigations.
Lawyers must follow the highest standards of professional ethics and inspire trust and confidence in society.
Mr. Ditta betrayed this trust and tried to hide behind his profession.
The investigation of Mr. Ditt was led by the Lancashire Serious Organized Crime Unit, which has already been sentenced to three counts of cocaine possession and now obstruction of justice, demonstrating our commitment to achieving fair punishment for the perpetrators.
Let this case serve as a warning to criminals that no one is beyond the reach of the law.
We'll find you and bring you to justice.
Scarborough was sentenced to 14 years in prison after pleading guilty to conspiring to supply heroin, cocaine and marijuana.
Another 35 people involved in the fraud were sentenced to 153 years for drug-related crimes.
