There have been almost daily reports of clashes between government forces and Renamo for two weeks, one of the most violent clashes since the armistice more than 20 years ago.
Renamo was once a prominent rebel movement that was supported first by the white Rhodesian authorities and then by the apartheid-era South African government as part of an effort to destabilize the country's independent government.
After the 1992 armistice, it became an opposition party.
Analysts believe that the country is unlikely to slide back into full-scale conflict, but recent events have made foreign investors and local residents nervous.
The stakes are high for a fast-growing economy, as the discovery of huge offshore gas reserves and coal deposits in the northwest could attract more than $50 billion in investment in the next few years from companies such as Rio Tinto, Vale from Brazil, Eni from Italy and Anadarko from the United States.
The ruling Frelimo party, a leading political force since 1975, and Renamo's party accuse each other of creating tensions.
Renamo's party says the government has been behind the latest clashes, attacking its members in Sofala province, Renamo's traditional stronghold, on October 17.
The attacks on former rebels then escalated when government forces attacked Renamo bases and attempted to kill Afonso Dhlakama, the group's leader, Fernando Mazanga, a Renamo spokesman, told the Financial Times.
The government blames Renamo for initiating the clashes, accusing the party of attacking soldiers.
President Armando Gebuza tried to allay fears of instability.
Gebuza told AFP, a French news agency, on Wednesday that Mr Dhlakama felt like a "loser" who wanted to use "everything left of his strength to try to prove that he can impose his own decisions on the government."
Both Frelimo and Renamo insist they want to avoid war.
However, fears rose after reports that Mazanga had announced Renamo's rejection of the 1992 peace agreement.
He told the Financial Times that he meant non-compliance with the agreement by the Frelimo party.
“Our goal is to return to negotiations, but with all seriousness,” Mazanga said.
Previous talks between the parties have done little to ease tensions, which have been exacerbated by a series of clashes this year.
“These are two influential people (Gebuza and Dhlakama) facing off with their foreheads,” said Joseph Hanlon, a lecturer at the Open University and an expert on Mozambique.
None of them is a good negotiator and none of them are willing to make the necessary concessions.
Renamo’s party, which is trying to push for electoral reforms, has already announced that it will boycott the municipal elections scheduled for November.
Presidential and parliamentary elections are scheduled for next year.
Some commentators interpreted this pressure as an attempt by a weakened movement to secure concessions and financial bonuses from the government.
The share of votes for Renamo has been declining since 1992, while the new party, the Mozambique Democratic Movement (MDM), which was founded by a former member of Renamo, is expected to improve its performance in this election.
Mr. Mazanga said that Mr. Gebuza, who was due to step down next year when his second term ended, wanted to destroy democracy in the country.
“He doesn’t want a multi-party democracy, he doesn’t want transparent elections, he doesn’t want peace because he doesn’t want to leave the presidency,” Mazanga said.
It is unclear what capabilities Renamo has, but it has already carried out devastating and swift attacks on police stations and cars on a key north-south highway.
Most of the skirmishes took place in Sofala province, which is a few hundred kilometers north of Maputo, but includes Beira, a port that mining companies including Rio Tinto and Vale use to export coal.
In June, Rio suspended the use of the railway tracks for about a week after Renamo threatened to attack the railway.
Mazanga was evasive when asked if Renamo would repeat this threat.
Renamo’s party wanted to “warn the international community that things are not going well in Mozambique,” Mazanga said.
Instability has increased discontent with the government, and many people are also concerned about corruption, slow development and the recent increase in kidnappings, says Fernando Lima, head of independent media company Mediacoop.
“People think that the government and the president are responsible for the future of the country, and they have to find a solution to these problems,” he said.
Omar Sultouan, a participant in the demonstration, said that people just want stability.
“No one cares about Renamo or Frelimo, they just want to restore peace, they want free access to roads,” he said.
