Power engineers of Dnipropetrovsk region began a unique program to save ... storks nests
In the old days, to bring storks to the court, the peasants on a high pole installed a wheel from the cart, and the heavy nest was well kept on it.
Such special supports have not been put for a long time, so storks have chosen poles of power lines - intertwined branches rely on wires, thanks to which the stork house is reliable.
Grandmother Anya, near whose house in the village of Ivanovka of the Petrikov district for twenty years lives a stork family, began to notice how the nest settles, despite all the efforts of its inhabitants.
Birds put new twigs on top, and the lower layer has already settled between the wires, is about to collapse.
Of course, pity the family of storks, who every year nested at the farmhouse, brought out and nursed over the summer three or four chicks, but I do not want to be without light.
As soon as the birds flew to the warm lands, Anna's grandmother called the Tsarichansky DEN, which owns the support.
I didn’t expect them to react so quickly.
When our specialists arrived in Ivanovka, they were surprised that the nest still holds, - said Sergey Berezovsky, technical director of DTEK Dniprooblenergo.
On the wires, which were, in fact, already inside the nest, weighing 150 - 200 kilograms, corrosion began.
At any time, the birds could die from an electric discharge.
And the locals risked being left without electricity due to damage to the wires.
Therefore, linear monters began the operation to save the nest, and not for the first time in our practice.
Ornithologists from Dnipropetrovsk National University helped, who developed a nest transfer scheme.
They also conducted trainings for employees of district networks.
The famous Dnepropetrovsk ornithologist Alexander Ponomarenko advised power engineers at all stages of nest reconstruction.
To begin with, it was estimated that there are more than 50 "apartments" in emergency condition in the region.
For their reconstruction, special metal platforms resembling a funnel were welded.
The base was braided with willow branches, and then the old nest was moved there.
According to experts, it is enough to lay old branches as a basis for the birds to recognize the nest and return to it.
Then they will build their own homes.
A month ago in the village of Peschanka Novomoskovsk district was reconstructed the first nest.
Next to the electrical support, a new reinforced concrete pillar was installed and a platform with an old, already inhabited nest was placed on it.
The whole operation cost the power engineers nine thousand hryvnias.
And the other day, the same housewarming took place in the village of Ivanovka, Petrikov district, on the outskirts of grandmother Ani.
Here the platform was fixed in the same place, only raised above the wires.
Ornithologists are sure that cautious, conservative birds will not even notice in the spring that their “apartment” has undergone major repairs.
Until the end of the year, the same reconstruction is expected by four more nests in Pokrovsky and Tsarichansky districts of Dnipropetrovsk region.
By the way, while some save rare birds, others mercilessly kill them.
Recently, the whole region flew sad news - in the village of Ust-Kamenka Apostolovsky district, on the day of the opening of the hunt for pheasants, poachers for fun shot the swan family that lived on the local pond.
Noble birds were not afraid of people at all - the locals fed them and did not offend them.
When the villagers heard the shots, they ran to the pond, four handsome swans were already lying on the water dead.
Now the staff of the Apostolovsky district police Department to find out who shot at the birds listed in the Red Book.
"Russian March" is becoming more popular
November 4, on the Day of National Unity, in Moscow will be agreed with the mayor's office "Russian March".
According to a survey by the Levada Center, support for the Russian Marches is growing - already 40% of citizens to varying degrees approve of the idea of holding them.
According to the “Levada-center”, 40% of citizens to varying degrees approve of the “Russian marches”: 11% of them are definitely positive and 29% are “rather positive”.
The popularity of the idea of "Russian marches" is gradually growing - in 2006, only 14% of Russians welcomed these actions, and in December 2010 the holding of such events was already supported by twice as many citizens (28%).
"Definitely negative" to "Russian marches" are only 7% of Russians, "rather negative" - 19%.
Another 35% could not formulate their attitude to this action.
