Previous Post:Obama’s campaign considered the exclusion of Biden in favor of Hillary Clinton
According to The New York Times, close advisers to President Barack Obama secretly considered replacing Vice President Joe Biden with Hillary Clinton on the 2012 electoral list.
This discovery is the most vivid sensation of all the expected book by Mark Halperin and John Hylemann about the 2012 campaign “Bets Doubled: The Game Changed 2012”.
The Times obtained a copy of the forthcoming book and reported Thursday night that the president’s closest aides conducted “large-scale focus group research and opinion polls in late 2011” to assess whether Biden’s exclusion could help raise fading hopes for Obama’s re-election.
According to political columnist Jonathan Martin, the book gives a detailed description of the attempt of senior officials of the campaign and the White house, namely the former head of the White house Bill Daly, to assess the effect of the appointment of former Secretary of state Clinton Vice President.
The possible replacement was a closely guarded secret at the Chicago campaign headquarters and the Oval Office.
Only six of the president’s closest advisers — including Daley, former Obama campaign chief Jim Messina, and former senior White House advisers David Axelrod and David Pluff — knew the replacement was under consideration.
The book, Bets Doubled, claims Daley was behind the effort to replace Biden despite their “close personal relationship,” but ultimately backed out when their data showed that adding Clinton to the electoral roll would not “improve substantially Obama’s chances.”
In an interview with Martin Daly confirmed that the administration was indeed considering replacing Biden with Clinton.
“I was very vocal about a lot of things, and that was one of them,” Daley told the newspaper.
You have to remember that the president was in terrible shape at the time, so we thought, "Oh my God, what are we going to do?"
Although Daley described the study as "a necessary test," Martin told CNN's Anderson Cooper that the campaign had invested heavily in examining whether the move would pay dividends on the vote.
“The campaign doesn’t spend that much money on polls and focus groups if they don’t take things seriously,” Martin said on the AK 360 program.
It is unclear, however, whether Obama knew his team was exploring the possibility of a replacement.
Martin told CNN that he asked Daly if his then-boss knew about the possible shuffling.
While Daley said he didn’t think the president “was aware” of a possible replacement, the former chief of staff admitted that “maybe” Obama knew.
Martin added that “The stakes are doubled” does not give a clear answer to the question of whether the results of political probing reached the Obama table.
Cooper asked Martin if he seriously believed that Obama was unaware of the study's possibility of excluding Biden from the electoral list.
“Maybe,” Martin replied.
