George Kerevan: Breaking with Europe gives Scots a choice
Another day, another horror story about independence.
This time we are warned that an independent Scotland will have to join the pan-European free movement zone as a condition of EU membership.
There comes a line of stories about passport control in Berwick and the border with barbed wire along Adrian's shaft.
True, Strathclyde pointed out the possible economic benefits of freer movements across the rest of Europe, though — predictably — this did not appear in the headlines.
Nor has anyone pointed out that EU member states spend a lot of time turning their formal rules around in ways that are convenient for them.
Since Scotland is not part of the Schengen area at the moment, continued non-compliance would be a cheap concession for Brussels to replace what it really wanted from the Scots.
So it's not a story that deserves attention.
And so old that it turned into a fossil: the first time I heard the “duck” that “independence means passport control” was at least 40 years ago.
And yet there is an interesting moment lost in the retelling of an old fairy tale.
Why should an independent Scotland obey the orders of Europe?
Why change the yoke of London to the yoke of Brussels, especially now?
Here’s the real European news: the great post-war plan to unite Europe has finally stalled.
With the euro crisis, the Europe project is officially dead.
Across the European Union, parties opposed to the EU or to the abolition of the euro as a single currency are gaining ground.
Even in Germany, the Eurosceptic Alternative for Germany party — founded just this year — emerged out of nowhere and won nearly five million votes in September’s federal election, thus effectively ousting the Free Democrats (similar to our Liberal Democrats) from the Bundestag.
There has always been domestic opposition to the plan to create a federal Europe.
However, the current economic crisis was a turning point.
The austerity measures imposed by Berlin and the European Central Bank, and the shackles imposed on national economies through the preservation of the single currency, have led many people to think that the Europe project has gone too far.
The euro crisis has little to do with national governments running excessive budget deficits — that was only true for Greece.
In fact, the Eurosystem has blocked its members at exchange rates favorable to German exporters, which German politicians want to keep.
Without the possibility of devaluation of the national currency, southern Europe finds itself at a pre-emptive disadvantage in terms of production opportunities in comparison with Germany.
The only saving means is to cut wages and government spending, which is actively supported by Berlin.
Behind the current problems of the budget and the currency is a deeper problem of Europe’s productive abilities.
As a result of a set of green energy measures implemented by Brussels — a cipher that means subsidizing French and German energy companies at the expense of the consumer — European industry pays twice as much for electricity and four times more for gas than in the United States.
These are paralyzingly unfavorable price conditions, as we have seen in Grangemouth.
No wage freeze in the world will stop the crushing victory of cheap US shale gas over the European petrochemical industry.
As a result, a revolt is brewing, especially in France, once the most ardent supporter of the EU.
After the war, the French political elite saw the EU as a way to control Germany and put Paris on a par with Washington.
But Berlin no longer needs Paris as a means of gaining political legitimacy, and has already imposed its own economic policies on Europe, leaving France’s shattered economy in distress.
The result is Marine Le Pen’s right-wing anti-EU National Front party has just won a crucial by-election, dropping the ruling Socialist Party into third place.
The Front is now the most popular party in France with 24 percent of the vote — a timely warning to British Labour that it cannot be assumed that a split among the right will automatically be in favor of the left.
What does Le Pen do with his newfound popularity among the French white working class?
She wants to use the EU elections next year to create a bloc in the European Parliament against the EU and against the single currency.
If, as is very likely, anti-EU parties gain support in these elections, such a bloc would be able to dominate the European Parliament for the first time.
Here’s my opinion: soon rising sentiments against the EU and against the single currency in Europe will merge to destroy the euro.
The EU will not disappear, but it will again become something of a vague “Europe of (sovereign) nations” that General de Gaulle liked.
Germany and a few dependent economies could save the euro, but France and southern Europe would recover their own currencies.
I assume that the UK is distancing itself from this project, hoping to get closer to the US.
Nevertheless, Washington’s growing interest in the Pacific indicates the likelihood that Britain will be left unattended in the cold Atlantic.
Where does that leave Scotland?
We can choose to become a region of (essentially) Little England.
Or we can protect our own economic interests, which means, among other things, sending Berlin and Brussels to hell.
I suspect Scotland will be able to do well under a looser European arrangement, provided we keep our currency.
Cooperation with other like-minded countries will be easier in a non-federal Europe of nations.
Otherwise, we should consider repeating Norway’s experience and preserving our economic independence.
The Scottish National Party government in Scotland is, oddly enough, the most successful political movement in Europe against austerity measures, winning an impressive majority in 2011 thanks to objections to spending cuts proposed (and implemented) by Labour Chancellor of the Exchequer Alistair Darling and the resulting Tory and Liberal Democrats coalition.
It would be absurd for Scotland now to vote for independence only to adopt austerity measures imposed by Berlin and Brussels.
Early puberty: getting older earlier
African-American and Latin American girls tend to reach puberty earlier than their white counterparts, research shows.
Physical changes do not mean puberty is near.
No evidence that hormones or other chemicals are to blame
Experts believe that the obesity epidemic may be one of the triggers of early puberty
The tendency to early puberty is not so pronounced in boys
Former CNN correspondent Pat Etheridge is a journalist specializing in child health and family issues.
Should a mother be scared if her daughter begins to develop breast rudiments and pubic hair at 7 or 8 years old?
At this week’s American Academy of Pediatrics annual conference in Orlando, Florida, pediatric endocrinologist Dr. Paul Kaplovitz explained that these early physical changes are quite common among American girls and represent a new norm.
“I spend a lot of time calming my parents — it doesn’t usually mean I’m going to have full sexual maturity,” Caplovitz said.
Obvious signs of development, such as growing breasts, pubic and armpit hair, and body odor, appear earlier in girls.
But there has been only a slight shift in the age of menarche (first menstruation) over the past four decades.
In the United States, the average age is 12.5 years, down from 12.75 in 1970.
“Once the breasts begin to develop, it takes at least two to three years before menarche,” said Kaplovitz, who is also the author of “Early puberty in girls: how to cope with this common problem.”
Time is the most accurate test of how puberty will progress.
There is a debate about what constitutes the actual onset of puberty, but it is considered “premature” when breast augmentation is accompanied by a sharp increase in growth up to 8 years.
In most cases, the process will slow down or stop - this is something that the pediatrician can monitor closely.
Faster progression may serve as the basis for tests by an endocrinologist to rule out serious problems, such as tumors or cysts.
There are procedures to delay early menstruation and prevent another consequence: premature aging of the bones, which can ultimately lead to slower growth and low growth in adulthood.
Recommendations for drug or hormone therapy are based on a child’s age, developmental level, growth rate, and emotional maturity.
Psychosocial aspects are also important.
Kaplovitz is cautious with medications, but admits that “repressing puberty can alleviate the behavioral problems and feelings of girls that they are different from their peers.”
Another big problem is clear: parents just don’t want their very young daughters to have menstruation.
“They’re worried about the risk of pregnancy or even how they’ll handle hygiene issues,” Kaplovitz said.
“It was a shock,” recalls one woman whose daughter began menstruating at age 10.
Although there were signs and we talked about menstruation, it was not emotionally ready.
She came home from school frightened and upset that she was the first among her friends.
There are many touted theories about the causes of early puberty.
However, there is no consistent evidence that hormones in milk or other foods, chemicals in the environment, or sexual messages in the media are to blame.
In boys - as in girls - puberty comes earlier.
Kaplovitz argues that the premise that holds the greatest weight is the obesity epidemic.
In 2001, he helped conduct a study of girls from 6 to 9 years old, which links the amount of fat in the body with the timing of puberty.
Other data support this finding, but there are many other contributing factors.
In this country, African American and Latin American girls tend to reach puberty earlier than their white counterparts.
There are different explanations.
Worldwide, early puberty seems to be influenced by everything from economic conditions and climate to genes.
Another mystery: although boys have facial and pubic hair at a younger age, the tendency to full early puberty is not as pronounced as in girls.
Other doctors attending the AAP conference confirmed the complexity of the topic.
The appearance of acne and pubic hair occurs even in infants and toddlers.
“We need to be careful about how we determine the true onset of puberty,” said Dr. Lawrence Silverman, a pediatric endocrinologist at Gorieb Children’s Hospital in Morristown, New Jersey.
Parents should not hesitate to receive instructions from a pediatrician about how to talk to their child.
“This could mean an earlier-than-expected conversation,” Kaplovitz explained.
If you stay calm, your child will usually respond well.
Girls who bloom early need confirmation that even when it happens earlier, this process is a normal part of life.
