Manufacturers of jet aircraft are at odds over the width of the seat when large orders are at stake
A fierce dispute has erupted between leading aircraft manufacturers over the width of tourist-class seats on long-haul flights, setting the tone for a fierce confrontation at this month’s Dubai Air Show.
The dispute revolves around the width of the seats provided on long-haul flights to economy-class passengers, whose interests are not always in the center of attention of airlines, while the amount of space allocated to them plays a key role in claims about the effectiveness of the latest aircraft offered by Airbus SAS and Boeing Co.
Airbus this week called for the introduction of an industry standard that would provide for a seat width of at least 18 inches (46 cm) in economy class cabins, but its main American competitor Boeing says that this should be decided by airlines.
The dispute comes at a time when aircraft manufacturers are competing in sales of increasingly larger versions of their twin-engine long-haul aircraft, and potentially record orders are expected at the November 17-21 event.
The layout of the rear of the aircraft - especially whether 9 or 10 people in a row - is central to the statements about the cost-effectiveness of new projects "mini-airbuses".
Boeing claims that its updated 777X will accommodate 406 people, based on seats in the economy class more than 17 inches wide, placed 10 in each row.
Airbus says a rival version of its A350 will carry 350 people in economy class on seats 18 inches wide, 9 in a row.
Aircraft giants often exchange blows on technical issues with the help of advertising in the professional press.
Airbus is now reaching out directly to the public ahead of the Dubai Airshow, where the 777X is expected to become the leader with more than 100 orders.
She recently demonstrated what the start of a new advertising war could be by showing financiers a slide depicting three people in a restaurant pinned to each other, titled "Would you agree to this?"
“Boeing offers long-haul flights on seats narrower than those of regional turboprop aircraft,” said Airbus sales manager John Leahy.
With a change in diet, people gain weight, but the aircraft seats have not changed dramatically.
Between the early 1970s, when the wide-body Boeing 747 set the standards for modern long-distance travel, and the turn of the century, the weight of the average American man between the ages of 40 and 49 increased by 10 percent, according to the U.S. Department of Health.
The waist circumference of an average 21st-century American male is 39.7 inches, according to U.S. Health Service statistics.
Airbus claims that its competitor adheres to the concept of seats in the 1950s, when the average waist circumference of those recently called the “reactive public” was already.
Airbus says it commissioned a study showing that an extra inch in the width of the seat improves sleep quality by 53 percent.
Boeing disputes Airbus’ seat size figures and says manufacturers shouldn’t get involved in decisions about how airlines balance fares and amenities.
According to her, studies show that the comfort of the cabin depends not only on the width of the seat.
“It really comes down to giving airlines the choice and opportunity to do what they think they need to do to be successful,” said Kent Craver, Boeing’s cabin specialist.
They do not want us to decide for them what will bring them profit.
They know their business better than anyone else.
For passengers, the issue is to increase the space on the sides, but for suppliers it is increasingly becoming a factor that can affect profits.
Behind this dispute is a race for aircraft orders valued at at at least $700 billion at catalog prices in the coming decades — enough to change the ratio of American and European exports.
As Reuters first reported in July, the location of the seats is exactly what fuels the rivalry in the battle between the newest jets.
Both Airbus and Boeing claim a 20% increase in profitability by one place in their latest twin-engine long-haul models compared to the market leader in this segment, the 365-seat Boeing 777-300ER.
The claimed characteristics of Boeing are based in part on a comparison of the 10-seater 777X series with the original 9-seater layout of the 777 constructive solution series.
The gain in unit cost is reduced when compared to the 10-seater layout currently in use.
“The reason Boeing is doing this is to squeeze in more seats and make its aircraft more competitive compared to our developments,” said Kevin Keniston, Airbus’s head of passenger comfort in Europe.
On the other hand, analysts say that cabins with full 10-seater rows for the existing 777s indicate that many passengers prefer a tight seating arrangement that can go hand in hand with lower fares.
“Eighteen-inch wide seats would be ideal for passengers, but the reality is that from a commercial point of view, Airbus’ offer is driven by a threat from the 777 model,” said interior designer Mary Kirby, founder and editor of the Runway Girl Network.
Airbus and Boeing do not supply seats, but offer a catalog of suppliers from which airlines can choose.
Traveling around the world, jet salesmen even carry roulettes with them to check out competing layouts.
While extolling comfort, all manufacturers also offer aircraft with a very dense cabin layout for budget airlines and regional flights.
Airbus offers the A350 with 10-seater rows, but says it hasn’t sold it yet.
Until recently, Airbus emphasized the need for additional cabin modifications, offering wider aisle seats on some of its aircraft.
Without the support of the only other manufacturer of large modern aircraft, as experts say, her call for a new industry standard is unlikely to “take off”, but can distract attention from the wave of sales of the 777X model.
New anti-nicotin vaccine may deprive the process of smoking pleasure
Scientists have developed an anti-nicotin vaccine that could deprive the process of smoking cigarettes pleasure.
One dose of the vaccine was able to protect mice from nicotine addiction for life.
Further tests are needed before human trials begin, which will take several years, but Professor Ronald Crystal of Weill Cornell College of Medicine in New York said the first results were encouraging.
"We very much hope that such a vaccine strategy could finally help the millions of smokers who tried to quit by trying all the methods available on the market today, but found that their nicotine addiction is strong enough to overcome it with these modern means," Cornell said.
The new vaccine contains a harmless virus that was designed to carry genetic information to produce antinicotine antibodies.
The virus selectively infects liver cells, which then begin to produce a steady stream of antibodies.
Antibodies track down any nicotine molecules in the blood, neutralizing them before they reach the brain, preventing the smoker from getting a nicotine kick.
In the tests, the vaccinated mice, who were subsequently given nicotine, continued their normal activities.
And mice that weren’t given the vaccine were “relaxed,” a sign that nicotine was reaching their brains, the researchers said.
These experiments are described in the journal Science Translational Medicine.
Previous tobacco vaccines failed because they contained antibodies.
To maintain a high level of antibodies, injections had to be done so often that they turned out to be expensive and impractical.
But the cost of the new vaccine is likely to be much lower because it turns liver cells into antibody factories.
Professor Crystal said that if the future human vaccine was completely safe, it could be given to children before they have the desire to try a cigarette, preventing nicotine addiction.
But it is more likely to be used by smokers to quit smoking.
“They’ll know that if they start smoking again, they won’t enjoy it because of the nicotine vaccine, and it can help them get rid of that habit,” he said.
British scientists said the results were interesting but warned that more research was needed.
