Owners of pawn shops in Singapore are doing well, while the middle class is experiencing difficulties
In a pawn shop in Singapore’s Bendemir shopping mall, Janani Amirthalinga pawns a gold bracelet, ring and earrings to pay for her daughter’s schooling.
“My husband and I just bought a house, so all my money is invested there,” says Ms. Amirthalinga.
Although she earns S$3,000 ($2,400) a month as an administrator and her husband also works, the family’s monthly income is not enough, she says.
Indeed, demand in various parts of Southeast Asia — where household debt is rising — is such that ValueMax, where it conducts its deal, this week became the third pawnshop listed on the Singapore Stock Exchange.
A jewelry loan is not just a quick way to get money ($1300 in Ms. Amirthaling’s case), but is almost as cheap as unsecured bank loans.
Typically, pawnshops in Singapore charge an effective annual interest rate of 17% — just above the 15.4% offered at the branch of United Overseas Bank, a local lender with a branch in the same mall.
However, pawn shops have the advantage that they do not require a credit check or proof of salary and can issue loans faster than banks.
Therefore, millions of people across the region are turning to pawn shops as families feel pressured by rising living costs and the rapid growth of household debt and consumer debt.
After five years of sustained growth following the global financial crisis and cheap credit fuelled by loose monetary policy in advanced economies, low- and middle-income families are turning to pawnshops to offset declining incomes as their economies slow down.
This week, Standard & Poor’s, a rating agency, cited an increase in family leverage, mainly due to rising mortgages, as a risk factor for Asian banks’ creditworthiness.
It said Malaysia, Thailand and Singapore had the highest household debt-to-gross domestic product ratio in Asia.
Malaysia topped the list with 80% of GDP compared to 60% in 2008.
Economists are also concerned about the high level of consumer debt in Thailand, which this week barely emerged from a technical recession.
On Thursday, data showed a continued decline in exports and weakening consumer demand.
“The bottom line is that with rising prices, people in the middle and bottom [income scales] will look for ways to replenish their incomes wherever they can,” says Song Seng-Wung, an economist at CIMB, a Malaysian bank.
Record-high gold prices in the past two years have intensified the rush with which people pawn their personal belongings as they take advantage of the opportunity to get paid for their family jewelry.
In Singapore, about 70% of the items laid in 200 pawnshops of the city-state are gold products.
“People say, ‘The price of gold looks good, let’s put down Grandma’s gold chain and get it back next month.’
In Thailand, the largest pawnshop operator EasyMoney has seen an increase in the number of customers using its branches in recent months, up to 20%.
The growth in the pawnshop business is such that ValueMax, the operator of the Bendemir branch and 15 others in Singapore, plans to expand not only in neighboring Malaysia, where it has four stores, but also outside Asia, says Yeah Lee Ching, CEO of ValueMax.
The company will fund the expansion using 60 percent of the S$66 million raised this week as a result of the Singapore Stock Exchange listing.
While some lenders have drawn fire from high interest rates, Ms Yeah says the pawnshop not only offers cheaper rates than other lenders, it also doesn’t increase debt directly.
“Customers are pawning items they already own, and monetizing personal assets doesn’t increase household debt,” she says.
The facility is gaining increasing public recognition as a means to obtain short-term, secured funding.
And at the same time pawnshops are used not only by those categories of people who are in a difficult financial situation.
Wealthy people in Singapore also use ValueMax branches, laying down gold bars or a Rolex watch that can give up to 60 percent of their purchase value in cash.
We see clients from all walks of life.
“These include wealthy individuals who need to borrow money for short-term commercial projects or investments, or small businesses who need to overcome temporary monetary difficulties,” says Yeah.
Sometimes they just need money very quickly.
