Passengers are now required to turn off their smartphones, tablets and other devices as soon as the plane door closes.
They should not restart them until the plane reaches an altitude of 10,000 feet and the captain gives a "good".
Passengers should turn off their devices again when the plane is down for landing, and not turn them on until the plane is on the ground.
Under the new guidelines, airlines whose aircraft are adequately protected from electronic interference can allow passengers to use these devices during takeoff, landing and taxiing, the FAA said.
Most new airliners and other aircraft modified so that passengers can use Wi-Fi at high altitudes are expected to meet these criteria.
Laura Glading, president of the Association of Professional Flight Attendants, welcomed the changes.
“Once the new policy is successfully implemented (and we are going to work closely with the carrier to achieve this), it will be a win-win option,” said Glading.
We are frankly tired of feeling “on duty at school” when it comes to this issue.
But an internet connection for surfing, exchanging emails, texting, or downloading data would still be banned at less than 10,000 feet, the agency said.
Passengers will be asked to switch their smartphones, tablets and other devices to airplane mode.
Thus, there are still no "Words with Friends" - an intellectual Internet game, which actor Alec Baldwin played on his smartphone in 2011, when there was a sensational incident: the actor was removed from the plane of American Airlines for refusing to turn off the device while the plane was at the exit of the landing.
And heavier devices, such as laptops, will still need to be put in the luggage compartment, as they can injure someone if they fly around the cabin.
Phone calls in flight will also continue to be banned.
The regulatory authority for phone calls belongs to the Federal Communications Commission, not the FAA.
FAA may lift ban on some electronic devices during takeoff and landing
Last month, Mark Rosenker of the National Transportation Safety Board, a national transportation safety expert at CBS News, said cell phones were still considered a risk.
“Cell phones are really a problem, not only because they can potentially interfere with navigation devices, but we know thanks to the FCC that they can interfere with cell towers when a plane is in the air,” Rosenker said.
An industry advisory committee set up by the FAA to look into the matter recommended last month that the government allow greater use of personal electronic devices.
In recent years, pressure has increased on the FAA in order to ease restrictions on their use.
Critics, such as Missouri Democratic Senator Claire McCaskill, argue that there are no good security reasons for the bans.
Observance of restrictions is also becoming increasingly difficult to ensure, as the use of devices has become ubiquitous.
Some studies show that up to a third of passengers forget or ignore instructions to turn off their devices.
The FAA began restricting passengers' use of electronic devices in 1966 in response to reports of interference to navigation and communication equipment when passengers began carrying FM radio receivers, high-tech gadgets of the time.
The new airliners are much more dependent on electrical systems than previous generations of aircraft, but they are also being developed and approved by the FAA as resistant to electronic interference.
Airlines have been offering passengers the use of Wi-Fi at cruising altitude for several years.
Aircraft modified for Wi-Fi systems are also more resistant to interference.
The vast majority of airliners are adapted for wider use of electronic devices according to new guidelines, Huerta said.
Today’s electronic devices typically emit radio signals of much lower power than previous generations of devices.
Devices for reading e-books, for example, emit only minimal signals when flipping pages.
But signals become more powerful when devices download or send data.
Among those who sought to ease restrictions on the use of electronic devices by passengers was Amazon.com.
In 2011, representatives of the company downloaded the entire airliner with their Kindle e-book readers and flew on it to check for problems, but never found them.
Members of the FAU advisory committee expressed mixed feelings about whether the use of the devices posed any risk.
Douglas Kidd of the National Air Passenger Association said he believes interference from the devices is real, even if the risk is minimal.
Other members of the committee said there were only isolated messages from pilots confirming that the devices could interfere with aviation systems, and most of those messages were very old.
However, the committee recommended that the FAA allow pilots to require passengers to turn off the devices while boarding the devices in reduced visibility.
A group of representatives of the tourism industry welcomed these changes, calling them a reasonable step towards passengers who now use a variety of technological devices.
“We are pleased that the FAA recognizes that passenger comfort is not incompatible with safety and security,” said Roger Dow, director general of the U.S. Travel Association.
