Two YMCA NSW employees were charged with sexual offences against children before charges were brought in 2011 against Caringbach child care worker Jonathan Lord, the Royal Commission on Child Sexual Abuse reported.
But the commission’s opening statement said it had “never dealt with cases of child sexual abuse within its organization.”
Chief Executive Officer Philip Hare was asked about one case where a YMCA employee was charged with child pornography offences and another case where a gym instructor at YMCA Caringbah Hall was convicted of sexual offences against children under his care in 1991.
Mr. Hare told Gail Furness, a lawyer assisting the commission, that he was aware of the first case but did not know of the second.
He acknowledged that the YMCA, in its opening speech to the commission, also made an inaccuracy, claiming that "there were external audits of the YMCA acknowledging that the YMCA is in the forefront of child safety."
The evidence presented to the commission indicates that the YMCA was notified that it had received the second-to-last of four possible assessments from a quality audit performed by the Department of Education and Communities in August of this year.
Mr. Hare, who joined the YMCA when he was 21, acknowledged that he and lower management had made a blunder by hiring Lord and also failed to provide a clear understanding of the staff's obligations regarding reporting child safety policy violations.
Earlier this year, Lord was convicted of sexual offences against 12 boys during his two years at the YMCA.
He was imprisoned for at least six years.
But Hare rejected the suggestion that YMCA’s corporate ethics prevented employees from reporting Lord’s child safety violations.
The staff testified that they had observed the violations, including Lord being alone with the children, personally caring for them, putting them on his lap, saying that he loved one of them and allowing them to play with his mobile phone.
Danielle Oakwell, who was under Lord's direction and asked to be trained in child protection because she was concerned about his behavior, testified that she found Jackie Barnath, the child custody manager for the YMCA's Caringbach branch, who was Lord's supervisor, "very intimidating and often difficult to reach."
The chief executive said he did not accept employees’ explanation that they were embarrassed to report the situation to their senior executives.
Rather, he said, their friendship with Lord led them away from the idea of having to report him.
Mr Hare said he had submitted to the New South Wales YMCA board his view that the lesson for the organization from the "Jonathan Lord incident" did not "concern the provision of information" by the staff, and the board agreed with him.
Mr Hare said the decision to force employees to sign confidentiality agreements shortly after the allegations surfaced was made by YMCA's Director General of Child Care, Liam Wheatley.
He said it was meant to prevent corruption of the evidence, but at the same time “overdone” and this decision was poorly implemented.
The New South Wales YMCA was not safe for children during Jonathan Lord’s tenure between 2009 and 2011, according to child molestation expert Professor Stephen Smallbone of Griffith University.
He said there were "serious problems" in recruiting, selecting, instructing, training and monitoring staff.
The hearing is postponed until December 20.
