Scientists have shed light on how the movements of a dog’s tail are related to its mood.
Earlier studies have shown that satisfied dogs wag their tail to the right (from a dog's point of view), while anxious dogs wag their tail mainly to the left.
But now scientists say other members of the canine family may notice these subtle differences in tail wagging and respond to them.
Professor Giorgio Vallortigara, a neuroscientist at the University of Trent, said: “It is well known that in humans, the left and right sides of the brain are involved in different ways in the formation of stimuli that cause positive or negative emotions.
Here we tried to look at this and other species.
In dogs, the right side of the brain controls the left side of the body and vice versa, and the two hemispheres play different roles in emotions.
To learn more about how dogs respond to the versatile twisting of the tails of other dogs, the researchers observed the animals as they watched movies about other dogs.
They measured the heart rate of the animals and analyzed their behavior.
We will probably soon understand why their tails sometimes go in one direction, and sometimes in the other.
Professor Vallortigara said: "We showed dogs videos of dogs - either naturalistic versions or silhouette - to get rid of any other distorting factors, and we could manipulate the movement of the tail and direct the tail more to the left or right."
When the animals saw that the otherwise unexpressive dog was moving its tail to the right (from the point of view of the wagging dog's tail), they remained completely relaxed.
But when they noticed that the tail leaned predominantly to the left (again in terms of the wagging tail of the dog), their heartbeats increased and they looked alarmed.
Professor Vallortigara said he did not think the dogs were intentionally communicating with each other through these movements.
In fact, he believes that dogs have learned from their experience what movements they should be worried about and what not.
He observes: “If there are multiple encounters with other dogs and often wagging their tails in one direction is associated with more friendly behavior, and the right side gives less friendly behavior, then the dog reacts based on this experience.”
The researchers say these findings could give owners, veterinarians and trainers a deeper understanding of their animal’s emotions.
Dog behavior expert John Bradshaw, a visiting researcher at the University of Bristol Veterinary School, said this was not the first study to test whether left and right sides matter for dogs.
Last year, a group of scientists from the University of Lincoln found that dogs turn their heads to the left if they look at an aggressive dog, and to the right if they look at a satisfied dog.
And in another study at the University of Victoria in Canada, he reported: “Dogs were more likely to approach a robot dog when the wagging of its tail was directed to the left rather than to the right, rather than becoming alarmed —the opposite behavior in relation to an Italian study.”
He said the differences could be due to the fact that dogs in various studies did not fully perceive animals in movies or robot dogs as dogs.
It could be useful to study how dogs respond to real dogs, he explained.
"While there is ample evidence from different mammals that the two hemispheres of the brain are used for different purposes, many details remain to be clarified, and dogs are no exception," he said.
However, given the ease with which their behavior can be recorded, it is likely that soon we will understand why their tails sometimes go in one direction and sometimes in the other.
