Pope Francis will install new cardinals of the Catholic Church for the first time in his term of office on February 22, the Vatican announced on Thursday.
The cardinals are the highest clergy in the Catholic Church after the pope, and it is they who elect the popes, so Francis will appoint his first group of people who will ultimately be involved in choosing his successor.
There are currently 201 cardinals.
However, after reaching the age of 80, the cardinal can no longer participate in the election of the pope - this is the prerogative of the group of 120 "cardinal electors".
