He said the pope usually names as many cardinals as needed to bring the number of cardinal electors back to 120, as well as as as many cardinals over the age of 80 as he wishes.
The Consistory next year will be of great importance because it will be the first since the election of Francis in March of this year, according to Valero.
At the moment, there is a kind of bias in favor of Europe and especially in favor of Italy.
“It will be interesting to see if the new pope appoints cardinals from other regions of the world to restore balance,” he said.
Forty percent of Catholics live in South America, but they are represented by a negligible number of cardinals.
They will also be the first elected cardinals since Francis formed the Council of Cardinals, a group of eight cardinals from around the world tasked with finding ways to reform the church.
In the past, Dad decided everything on his own.
“Now Francis has selected eight cardinals to help him,” Valero said.
He said it was “quite possible” that Francis would turn to the cardinals for advice.
But we were not in this situation before - all this is for the first time for us.
Valero said the popes used to appoint cardinal bishops from major parishes, but Francis "is full of surprises — so we don't know who he's going to name."
