Obama's Voter Despair
I voted for President Obama twice, sharing the hope for change.
He says Obama has allowed Republican obstructionism to derail laudable efforts.
Obstructionism cannot justify problems with the Obama-reformed health care system’s website, drone attacks
The memoirs of the 2008 Obama campaign are a sad reminder of what could have been.
Nathaniel P. Morris is a second-year medical student at Harvard University.
I'm reading a terribly sad book these days.
I thought that this book would inspire me in times of discouragement in my second year of medical school and revive a sense of hope in me.
It’s called “Audacity to Win,” and it’s a memoir of Barack Obama’s 2008 presidential campaign.
When I finish writing reports on my patients in the evening and go to bed, this book takes me back to a time when politics inspired millions of people and performances could be breathtaking.
The election victory turned out to be impressive, and the leading news programs paused to reflect on this historical moment.
My classmates cried with joy, and my parents kept all the newspapers they could find.
A young team of strategists was to come to the White House, and the people were ready for change.
When Obama took office in 2008, his support rate was 82%.
Then I close the book.
Returning to the present is a rude awakening, like pulling out of a dream.
It’s hard to remember those days of optimism — they seem like a distant memory, a sad reminder of missed opportunities.
In the years since I dropped my first ballot, changes have indeed taken place.
It was something I couldn't even imagine.
I commend Obama for his great and varied accomplishments, from passing the Affordable Care Act to withdrawing our military from Iraq, repealing the “Don’t Ask, Don’t Tell” rule, and killing Osama bin Laden.
Moreover, I believe that party obstructionism has blocked too many attempts to move our country forward: immigration reform, the ability to choose public health care, and the closure of the Guantanamo base, among others.
But after countless times standing on the side of the Obama administration, defending it in front of colleagues and peers, I’ve run out of explanations that I can provide.
I have reached a point of political despair.
Republican obstructionism cannot explain permission to wiretap foreign leaders or drone strikes on innocent children in other countries.
He cannot explain the collection of data on Americans’ privacy by the National Security Agency or the prosecution of whistleblowers who reveal government misconduct.
He cannot explain the murder of American citizen Anwar al-Awlaki without trial or failure to meet the limits of government funding and spending during presidential campaigns.
He cannot justify the conclusions of the report, which says that the White House’s efforts to silence the media are “the most aggressive ... since the Nixon administration.”
And more recently, it cannot justify failing to develop a simple website for more than three years after the signing of the Affordable Care Act.
I don't know if I should have expected that.
Should I have understood at the age of 18 that the leadership may be at odds with the political campaigns that precede it?
Obviously, running for office is not a predictable agenda, as our public dialogue will be shaped by the opposition political party and by random events such as the Newtown massacre.
Nevertheless, from all the examples I have listed above, it can be seen that they were largely the administration’s own choice.
And that's what worries me the most.
I voted for Obama again in 2012, but not because I was enthusiastic about his candidacy.
Mitt Romney was an unintelligible and crude alternative, it seemed that he was unable to make a decision on his own policies or views.
I believed that in his second term, Obama, free from the pressure of future elections, would live up to the hopes that we have heard for so long.
However, when Obama’s rating dropped below 45% this week, it became much more difficult to return to 2008 through this book.
It makes me yearn for many promises that have faded away.
This week, I read the part of the book that describes how Clinton inflicted a resounding defeat on Obama in the Pennsylvania primary.
At a meeting to analyze the reasons for the failure, he told his employees that they should return to normal and stay true to their goal.
“I want us to get our appeal back,” he said.
We have to remember who we are.”
Five years have passed, Mr. President, and I completely agree with you.
The opinions expressed in this comment belong exclusively to Nathaniel Morris.
