ISLAMIST Mohamed Morsi promised a "new Egypt" when he took the oath of office, becoming the country's first freely elected president, replacing Hosni Mubarak, who was deposed 16 months ago.
In his inauguration before the Supreme Constitutional Court, Morsi also became the first freely elected Islamist president of the Arab world and the fifth head of state in Egypt after overthrowing the monarchy some 60 years ago.
He took the oath before 18 judges in black robes in a courthouse on the banks of the Nile, built in the style of an ancient Egyptian temple.
