Travel through mud, rivers and jungles to provide free medical care
Dr. Georges Bwelle provides free medical care in rural Cameroon
Bwelle and his team spend almost every weekend taking hundreds of patients
There aren’t many doctors in this West African country — just one in 5,000.
Vote here or through your mobile device
Dr. Georges Bwelle is one of the 10 main characters of CNN 2013.
You can vote for him or any of the other 10 main characters to make him the CNN Hero of the Year.
This person will receive $250,000 to continue his outstanding work.
For 21 years, Georges Bwelle saw his father come back to life and again fall unconscious, wandering through hospitals that were not equipped properly to help him.
Jamef Bwelle was injured in a car accident in 1981 near Yaoundé, the capital of Cameroon.
At first, he only had a broken arm, but the resulting infection spread to the brain and caused a hematoma that reminded of itself for the rest of his life.
“There were no neurosurgeons in Cameroon,” Bwelle said.
If we had the money, we'd take him out of Cameroon.
Instead, Bwelle accompanied his father to overcrowded clinics and hospitals for years, receiving whatever treatment they could get.
“It’s not easy,” Bwell said.
You can leave home at 5 a.m., run to the hospital to be the first, but you are not the first.
A lot of patients.
Some may die because they have to wait.
The situation hasn’t changed much since Bwelle’s father passed away in 2002.
According to the World Health Organization, there is only one doctor per 5,000 people in Cameroon.
For comparison, the ratio in the United States is one doctor per 413 people.
And even if Cameroonians could see a doctor, many of them would not be able to afford it.
Two out of five people in this country live below the poverty line, and almost three-quarters of health spending in this country is private.
“Their only problem is poverty,” Bwelle said.
“And because of poverty, they can’t enjoy their lives.”
Seeing the suffering of his father and many of his compatriots, Bwelle was determined to do something about it.
Last year, Dr. Georges Bwelle and his team of volunteers performed 700 free surgeries.
He himself became a doctor and works as a vascular surgeon at the Central Hospital of Yaoundé.
He also founded the non-profit ASCOVIME, which organizes trips to the countryside on weekends to provide free medical care.
Since 2008, he and his group of volunteers have assisted nearly 32,000 people.
Almost every Friday, he and up to 30 others are packed into vans, tied to roofs with medical supplies, and driven across rough terrain to visit villages in need.
They don’t always have luck.
More than once they had to push cars through rivers and mud.
But when they arrive, they are greeted as real heroes: it’s a celebration with songs and dances and the best spaces the locals can offer.
Free medical care in these villages is indeed a cause for celebration, and Bwelle with his broad smile and boundless energy is more than happy to join the fun.
The next morning, the team begins to receive hundreds of patients.
“We take 500 people on every trip,” Bwelle said.
They come from all over the county within 60 kilometers of the village, and they come on foot.
Each of these weekend clinics provides a variety of medical services.
Many people receive treatment for malaria, tuberculosis, malnutrition, diabetes, parasites and sexually transmitted diseases.
Others may get crutches, donated glasses, or free birth certificates — documents needed for school that many poor families simply can’t afford.
In the evenings, the team performs simple operations under local anesthesia.
Operations are usually performed in a school building, municipality, or in a house; after the procedure, patients get up and go to the postoperative area to make room for the next person.
Using a generator to illuminate the operating and sanitary handling of equipment, Bwelle and his volunteers work until early Sunday morning.
This is an unbearable pace, but the dedication of the brigade usually helps to support the village musicians.
"They're beating the drums all night so we can stay awake and keep working," Bwelle said.
On Sunday, the crew members head back to the city, tired but proud of their work.
This group of Cameroonian doctors and international medical students have performed 700 free surgeries over the past year, and they know that their help can make a huge difference to those they help.
One person explained that the free hernia surgery he received would allow him to work again.
“It will change the future for me and my family,” he said.
In addition to these weekend clinical appointments and hospital work, Bwelle also works nights at private medical clinics around Yaoundé.
It is this second job, he said, that provides 60% of the funding to his nonprofit organization; the rest is covered by private donations.
"I don't even know when he's sleeping," said Kathy O'Malley, a second-year medical student at Drexel University in Philadelphia, a volunteer in Bwell's group.
He is always either in the hospital or trying to make money for the organization so that these campaigns can continue.
For future doctors and nurses like O’Malley, coming from the US and Europe to join Bwella in carrying out his tasks, this is an opportunity for practice they would never get at home.
"We were given the opportunity to assist in surgeries where we helped remove blood stains or hold tools for Dr. Bwelle," O'Malley said.
As a sophomore, you would never get such an opportunity in America.
Volunteer students usually pay for their own travel to Cameroon, often arriving with donated medicines.
But upon arrival in Yaoundé, their food, transportation, and training are paid for by Bwelle.
"He's a hero, no doubt," O'Malley said.
He gives his life to this organization, and his desire to help the people of Cameroon is endless.
For Bwell, almost constant workload is not a difficult test.
To help others live a happy life, to fulfill the promise made to his father, is what brings him great joy.
“I’m so happy when I do this job,” Bwelle said.
And I think of my father.
I hope he sees what I'm doing.
I do this to make people laugh to reduce their pain.
Go to the ASCOVIME website and see how you can help.
