The Agency “Rosbalt” was deprived of the status of the media for obscene language
On October 31, the Moscow City Court decided to invalidate the license to register the Rosbalt agency, Lenta writes.
Roskomnadzor insisted on depriving the agency of the status of the media - for systematic and gross violations of the law on the media.
During the process, an unpleasant precedent was created: the court considered it possible to close the media, effectively denying the publication the right to make counterarguments.
What is Rosbalt
CJSC "Information Agency Rosbalt" was established in St. Petersburg in 2000.
In the following years, the agency opened a second head office in Moscow and a number of regional divisions.
The agency also has representative offices in the countries of the former USSR.
Since 2001, Rosbalt has developed and functioned as a federal information and analytical agency.
By the mid-2000s, the agency was on the list of the most recognizable private online media in Russia.
At the same time, Rosbalt has always occupied a rather specific niche: the core of the agency’s exclusive publications were (and still are) notes with reference to sources in law enforcement agencies.
Talk about the proximity of the publication to the security forces continued throughout the existence of the agency.
Along with the fact that Rosbalt had an extensive base of sources in various departments, in favor of such assumptions, it was said that Natalya Chaplina, the wife of Viktor Cherkesov, was at the head of the project.
At the same time, Chaplina’s role in the leadership of Rosbalt is not completely clear: she is most often called the “project manager”.
The general director of the agency is Larisa Afonina, the editor-in-chief is Nikolai Ulyanov.
Recently, Rosbalt did not appear in the ratings of the federal media - neither by citation nor by audience.
In October, the agency took 25th place in the ranking of attendance of Russian media sites according to LiveInternet.
According to the same LiveInternet, the average daily audience of the site rosbalt.ru is about 150 thousand unique visitors (and up to 500 thousand views), monthly - about three million unique visitors.
Among the most popular materials for the last five months are notes about the Kremlin’s helplessness in relations with Ukraine, the death of the soloist of the group “King and Fool”, and pogroms in the capital city of Biryulev.
The conflict between Rosbalt and Roskomnadzor began in July 2013, when amendments to the media law came into force, banning journalists from swearing.
The Agency found prohibited language in two published on the Agency’s website videos (“Dzhigit from Krasnodar” and “Pussy Riot desecrated oil rigs”).
The other parties are described differently.
Roskomnadzor on the basis of the discovered video materials accused Rosbalt of gross and systematic violation of the law on the media and appealed to the court with a demand to take away the agency’s license.
Rosbalt stated that the claims of the department are incorrect: firstly, the videos were not editorial materials, secondly, the material words in them were disguised, and, thirdly, immediately after the warning, the videos were removed from the site.
Representatives of the agency appealed the claims of Roskomnadzor in the world court - and when on October 22, 2013 the Moscow City Court accepted the claim of Roskomnadzor, the consideration of these complaints was still ongoing.
However, on the 25th, the justice of the peace decided not in favor of Rosbalt: the editor-in-chief Nikolai Ulyanov was found guilty of violating the code on administrative offenses and fined 20 thousand rubles - 10 thousand for each video.
Obviously, this predetermined the outcome of the hearing in the Moscow City Court - if we abandon the idea that the outcome could have been decided even earlier.
On October 31, the court decided to invalidate the certificate of registration of Rosbalt, effectively depriving the agency of the status of the media.
It cannot be said that Rosbalt remained alone during this confrontation.
The agency was supported by deputies of the State Duma (a statement addressed to the head of Roskomnadzor Alexander Zharov on October 10 was signed by 26 deputies; the document itself was submitted at the initiative of the Communist Party of the Russian Federation).
The head of the Union of Journalists of Russia Vsevolod Bogdanov, the chairman of the Moscow Union of Journalists Pavel Gusev and the head of the Presidential Council for Human Rights Mikhail Fedotov said about the illegality of the closure of the publication.
Moreover, according to Bogdanov, the leadership of Roskomnadzor even gave him some guarantees that it would not come to the revocation of the license.
The trial of Rosbalt showed that under whose jurisdiction the media is safer in Russia today is a big question.
Syria destroyed equipment for chemical weapons
Syria has destroyed all declared chemical weapons production facilities, the Organization for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons has acknowledged.
Damascus completed this first phase of disarmament one day before the deadline.
Until November 1, Syria was supposed to destroy production and other auxiliary facilities designed to prepare chemical warfare agents for use.
The destruction of the stockpiles of toxic substances or their chemical components should be completed by mid-2014.
According to the representative of the OPCW, toxic substances are currently in sealed storage.
International inspectors went to Syria after more than 1,400 people were killed in a chemical attack on the outskirts of Damascus on August 21.
The main task of the inspectors was not to waste time - not to allow the Syrian authorities to produce more chemical weapons - and destroy the infrastructure for mixing chemicals and ammunition.
These production facilities will now be closely monitored to prevent them from being repaired.
The next milestone is mid-November: by that time, the OPCW and the Syrians should agree on a detailed plan to destroy existing stockpiles of toxic substances.
There are a lot of questions here.
Where will they be destroyed?
Who will provide the equipment for this?
All Syrian statements will be carefully checked by Western intelligence services.
They will readily advise the inspectors of new sites for inspection if there are grounds to suspect that Damascus is not completely frank.
The United States believes that the shelling was carried out by regular troops.
Syria and Russia insist that this is the work of the Syrian rebels.
The international community demanded that the Syrian leadership, in accordance with the agreement reached with the mediation of Russia, destroy or put out of service all capacities for the production of shells, toxic gases and liquids and for filling shells with these substances.
Now that this stage has been passed, the next step should be the destruction of the chemical weapons already available to the Syrian army.
It is assumed that this arsenal may contain more than 1,000 tons of nerve agents, mustard skin gas and other banned chemicals stored in several dozen different places.
For its destruction, it is necessary that the OPCW and the Syrian authorities first agree on a timetable for action - this is given two weeks.
The head of the OPCW field operations, Jerry Smith, told the BBC that his inspectors “personally monitored the destruction of equipment.”
“They no longer have the ability to further produce or mix chemical weapons,” he said.
The OPCW said in a statement that the inspectors visited 21 of the 23 sites in Syria and made sure that the factories for the production of shells and toxic substances are either destroyed or rendered unusable.
The remaining two facilities are too dangerous to be inspected, the document said, but the equipment from there has been transported and inspected by OPCW specialists.
According to Smith, the process of destroying the infrastructure for the production of chemical weapons was “particularly difficult”, as it had to work in the context of the ongoing conflict.
In early October, the OPCW won the Nobel Peace Prize, however, according to Smith, there is no time to celebrate this with inspectors yet - they were too busy with work.
John Kerry says in his unprecedented admission that U.S. spying “went inappropriately far”
John Kerry has shown a softening of tactics to protect U.S. surveillance programs, making an unprecedented admission that in some cases U.S. spying has “went inappropriately far.”
The Secretary also admitted that he was guilty, along with Barack Obama, of being “on autopilot” at the time of Edward Snowden’s high-profile revelations about NSA spying.
These leaks put the U.S. government at the center of a diplomatic row with its allies.
Speaking via video link at an open government conference in London, Mr Kerry said: “There is no doubt that the president and I, and other members of the government, actually took some of the things going on on autopilot because that possibility already existed — both during World War II and during the very difficult years of the Cold War, and certainly 9/11.”
He then became the first senior member of the U.S. government to admit that U.S. espionage had gone too far, but stressed that no rights had been violated.
He said: “In some cases, this has gone inappropriately far.
And the president is determined to shed light on this issue and explain himself to people, and is now conducting a thorough analysis to ensure that no one has a sense of abuse.
I assure you, there is no abuse of innocent people in this process.”
Mr. Kerry insisted, however, that the NSA acted for good reasons and that his surveillance operations saved many lives.
He added: “We’re working in a new world where people are willing to blow themselves up.
There is radical extremism in the world, reckless and determined to kill people, blow up people and attack governments.
And if you were able to intercept it, stop it before it happens?
We actually prevented plane crashes, building explosions and people being killed because we were able to learn about these plans in advance.”
Meanwhile, U.S. lawmakers will head to Europe to help resolve issues surrounding alleged U.S. spying abroad and convince Europeans to continue joint counterterrorism efforts with the U.S., the chairman of the Senate Subcommittee on European Affairs said on Thursday.
Connecticut Senator Chris Murphy said he had spoken to members of the European Parliament and others this week and was concerned about their threats to stop participating in anti-terrorism organizations due to frustration over National Security Agency surveillance.
“It’s really important for U.S. national security interests that Europeans remain our supporters in our common anti-terrorism efforts,” Murphy, a first-term Democrat who chairs the Senate Foreign Relations Subcommittee on European Affairs, said in an interview from Washington.
“And I’m going to Europe to make it clear that we must continue to cooperate in the fight against terrorism, despite their anger about these NSA programs.”
News that the NSA has collected millions of phone records in Europe has worsened relations with some U.S. allies, though the head of the agency said this week that they were inaccurate and reflected a misunderstanding of the metadata that NATO allies collected and shared with the U.S.
Other revelations cited documents released by Snowden showing that the NSA monitored German Chancellor Angela Merkel’s mobile phone, as well as the phones of some 34 other world leaders.
