In the new composition of public monitoring commissions will increase the influence of jailers
Today, the Council of the Public Chamber (OP) can approve the new composition of public supervisory commissions (NOCs) in 43 regions of Russia.
If the option put to the vote is adopted, the lobbyists of the security forces will increase their influence.
ONCs are social structures that control the conditions of detention in places of deprivation of liberty.
The cases of Sergei Magnitsky and Leonid Razvozzhayev, the unrest in the Kopei colony - it is through the ONC that most resonant incidents behind bars get publicity.
There is a struggle for control over the ONC between human rights defenders and lobbyists of the security forces.
At the meeting of the OP working group on the formation of ONC, I proposed to make the experience of human rights activities a criterion for selection.
“It was not accepted, and they formed lists without working out the criteria,” Valery Borshchev says.
Borshchev is the current chairman of the Moscow Monitoring Commission and the Association of Independent Observers, the all-Russian structure of human rights defenders dealing with prison problems.
When he was a State Duma deputy from Yabloko, he developed a law regulating the activities of the ONC.
The OP Council must vote for the composition of the ONC in 43 regions of the country.
Less than a thousand applicants are applying for 1,800 vacancies, and in Ingushetia and Kabardino-Balkaria, competitions could not be organized due to the lack of candidates.
The OP promises to organize additional recruitment for vacant places.
The DEC of Moscow is one of the few commissions with a competition, despite the fact that in the new composition instead of 20 there will be 40 participants.
According to Borshchev, in the current composition of the capital’s commission 11 human rights defenders and 9 security forces, and in the version that is on the vote in the OP, the ratio changes by 17 to 23.
At the same time, 30 human rights activists wanted to get to the capital commission.
But the new composition can re-enter the representative of the “Combat Brotherhood” Vyacheslav Kalinin.
He was a member of the ONC for three years, but never visited the prisoners.
Borshchev believes that the security forces, having appointed their chairman of the ONC, will be able to make the work of human rights defenders unbearable, so human rights defenders do not exclude a collective withdrawal from the commission.
In their opinion, the promotion of the security forces is coordinated by a member of the ONK Anton Tsvetkov, who heads the "Officers of Russia" - an organization that defends the interests of law enforcement agencies.
“I don’t eat babies on the back of the truck,” Anton Tsvetkov told RBC daily.
He denies lobbying for the promotion of any lists and says that he does not intend to prevent human rights defenders from visiting the arrested oppositionists.
According to Tsvetkov, he was not even interested in which list is now voted in the OP.
He considers the disclosure of Borshchov information a form of pressure.
A possible success of human rights defenders is the planned change of leadership of the Chelyabinsk ONK.
Its former leaders will be removed due to last year's Cope riots.
The Public Chamber concluded that the leadership of the local commission ignored the problems of prisoners.
But the ONC of Rostov-on-Don can move from human rights defenders to security forces.
From the new lists “missed” the human rights chairman of the local Commission, but was one of his opponents, despite the fact that in May 2013 the Federal Public Chamber excluded him for unethical behavior.
Lists of the Moscow and Rostov commissions Borshchev considers "the revenge for Kopeysk".
The revelations of Nadezhda Tolokonnikova did not affect the ONK of Mordovia, which is considered “forceful”: only one human rights activist wanted to join the new composition, and she did not even accept documents for the competition.
Council member Nikolai Svanidze told RBC daily that he voted against the proposed list, as he is outraged by the situation in Moscow and Rostov-on-Don.
He sent it to other council members.
His OP colleague Pavel Gusev says he voted in favor because he likes the proposed Moscow list.
Deputy Secretary of the OP Vladislav Grib, who is also a member of the Research Institute of the Federal Penitentiary Service, coordinated the compilation of ONC lists.
Grib told RBC daily that he does not believe it is correct to divide candidates for human rights defenders and security forces and does not agree that the chairmen of the commissions have enough powers to impede the work of its members.
The mushroom is not taken to predict the results of the vote of the OP council.
If the proposed list is rejected today, the amended version will be put to a vote in the coming days.
Australian woman appeals against jail time in Thailand
A 21-year-old Sydney woman sentenced to 15 days in prison on the island of Phuket for falsely claiming she was attacked by a taxi driver appealed the verdict and was released on bail.
Stevie Rochelle Bamford was initially found guilty on June 15 by the Phuket Provincial Court of filing a false claim following a report by Thai police that a local taxi driver had carried out the attack on the night of Sunday June 10, while two other men were holding her down.
However, CCTV footage later revealed that she returned safely to her hotel after breaking up with her Australian boyfriend.
Phuket police interrogated Bamford for two days before she confessed to fabricating the story.
Prior to the trial, she was held in local police cells.
Bamford was sentenced to 15 days in a general-regime detention centre on the outskirts of Phuket rather than an adult women's prison.
She is the daughter of former Australian League player Peter Tunks, who approached the Foreign Office in Canberra for help for his daughter.
Tanks told the Sydney Sunday Telegraph that the entire family was "extremely concerned" about her daughter's well-being and was waiting for her to return to Australia.
“Obviously, it was an alarming time, but we hope she comes home safely as soon as possible,” Tanks said.
Bamford appealed her sentence and was released on 50,000 baht bail.
According to reports in Australia, she is currently spending her vacation in the resort area of Krabi in southern Thailand.
Thailand-based legal sources said Bamford is currently represented by a local lawyer in Phuket, but warned that the appeal could result in a court extending her sentence to two years and forcing her to serve time in an adult prison.
However, after the recent murder of Australian travel agent Michelle Smith in Phuket, Thailand may also seek to restore its undermined tourist image, which will lead to an acquittal.
